	<div class="content-prose">
		<h2>Why Finish Your Basement in Utah?</h2>
		<p>
			If you bought a home in one of Utah's booming new construction neighborhoods — Saratoga Springs, Eagle Mountain, Lehi, Herriman — there's a good chance your basement is still unfinished. That's hundreds or even thousands of square feet of unused space sitting below your main floor.
		</p>
		<p>
			Finishing your basement isn't just about adding square footage. It's about adding value, flexibility, and comfort. Whether you need a mother-in-law apartment to accommodate aging parents, extra bedrooms as your family grows, a dedicated play space so toys aren't taking over your main floor, or rental income potential, a finished basement gives you options.
		</p>

		<h2>What Makes Bowka Different?</h2>
		<p>
			Basement finishing is one of our core specialties. We've worked on dozens of basements across Utah County, Salt Lake County, and Davis County — from basic family rooms to fully equipped mother-in-law apartments with kitchens, bathrooms, and separate entrances.
		</p>
		<p>
			We know Utah code requirements inside and out, including egress window specs, ceiling height minimums, and bedroom requirements. We handle permitting, pass inspections on the first try, and finish on schedule. Most importantly, we treat your home with respect and keep you informed every single day.
		</p>

		<h2>Common Basement Layouts We Build</h2>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Family Room + Storage</strong> — Open-concept entertainment space with built-in storage for seasonal items, sports gear, and holiday decorations.</li>
			<li><strong>Bedroom + Bathroom</strong> — One or two bedrooms with a shared or private bathroom, perfect for teens, guests, or rental income.</li>
			<li><strong>Mother-in-Law Apartment</strong> — Full apartment with kitchen or kitchenette, bathroom, bedroom, living area, and separate entrance. These are increasingly popular in Utah as multi-generational living becomes more common.</li>
			<li><strong>Home Theater + Bar</strong> — Dedicated movie room with tiered seating, sound insulation, and a wet bar for entertaining.</li>
			<li><strong>Home Office / Gym</strong> — Quiet workspace away from the main floor or a home gym with rubber flooring and wall-mounted equipment.</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Basement Finishing Timeline & What to Expect</h2>
		<p>
			Here's what a typical basement finishing project looks like from start to finish:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Week 0:</strong> Design consultation and estimate. We measure your space, discuss your vision, and provide a detailed proposal.</li>
			<li><strong>Weeks 1-2:</strong> Permit submission and approval. Utah County typically takes 1–2 weeks. We handle all paperwork.</li>
			<li><strong>Weeks 3-4:</strong> Framing, electrical rough-in, plumbing rough-in. Walls go up, outlets and light switch locations are established.</li>
			<li><strong>Weeks 5-6:</strong> Insulation, drywall, and texture. Inspections happen during this phase.</li>
			<li><strong>Weeks 7-8:</strong> Paint, trim, doors, and flooring installation.</li>
			<li><strong>Weeks 9-10:</strong> Final electrical and plumbing fixtures, finish carpentry, and final walkthrough.</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
			Total project time: <strong>6–10 weeks</strong>, depending on complexity. We stay on schedule and communicate clearly if anything changes.
		</p>

		<h2>Egress Windows: What You Need to Know</h2>
		<p>
			If you're adding a bedroom in your basement, Utah building code requires an <strong>egress window</strong> — a window large enough for emergency escape and rescue access. Egress windows must meet specific size requirements (minimum 5.7 square feet of opening, minimum 24" height and 20" width) and be paired with a code-compliant window well with a gravel base and ladder or steps.
		</p>
		<p>
			We install egress windows on every basement bedroom. It's not optional, and it's a critical safety feature. We handle excavation, window well installation, and backfill as part of our basement finishing service.
		</p>

